ch.ecma.csta.binding

Class SystemRegister

  • java.lang.Object
    • ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
      • ch.ecma.csta.binding.SystemRegister
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class SystemRegister
extends ch.ecma.csta.CastorObject
implements java.io.Serializable

    This request allows the application to register for changes in the status of either one specific Tlink or all administered Tlinks. The application can register to receive a SystemStatus request each time the status of the Tlink(s) changes.

    ChangeSysStatFilter Parameters
    requestedStatusFilter Conditional Specifies the set of System Status Types that will be filtered (not sent) by the switching function. The only supported System Status Types are Normal and Disabled, and their values can be true (filtered) or false (sent). All other System Status Types default to true (filtered).

    Note that the SystemRegisterRequestPrivateData object has an invertFilter parameter. When this invertFilter is set to true, the sense of the requestedStatusFilter is reversed. For example: usually, setting the Normal type to false and the Disabled type to true would result in the application receiving Normal System Status events, but Disabled events would be filtered. However, if the invertFilter is set to true, then the application would receive Disabled events. but Normal events would be filtered.

    CSTA Functional Implementation:

    1. The SystemRegisterRequestPrivateData object in the SystemRegister request is used to request notification of changes in Tlink status for either one specific switch or all configured switches.
    2. The sysStatRegisterID parameter returned in the positive acknowledgement is used to identify the registration over which system services will be sent. The sysStatRegisterID is also used when cancelling the system registration.
    3. The number of simultaneous system registrations allowed is switching function dependent. When the limit is reached, subsequent System Register service requests will result in negative acknowledgements from the switching function.
    4. The requestTypes parameter specifies which system services are to be issued by the switching function to the registering computing function.
    5. The requestedStatusFilter parameter allows the computing function to choose the System Status Types for which no SystemStatus service requests should be issued by the switching function. If the System Status service is not being requested (in the requestTypes parameter), then the actualStatusFilter parameter does not apply and will not be provided. The actual system status filter is provided in the actualStatusFilter parameter in the positive acknowledgement.
    6. An implementation that does not support all System Status Types will nevertheless accept the System Register service even if the requestedStatusFilter cannot be provided. The service acknowledgement indicates the actual set of System Status Types that will be filtered. This means that the actual set of filtered types returned in the positive acknowledgement may include additional types to be filtered (or fewer types generated by the switching function) than what was requested in the service request.
    7. If explicit registration is not supported, all system services (for example, System Status, Request System Status) and System Status Types (for example, Initializing, Enabled) supported by the switching function will be provided to the computing functions. Note that the computing function will be prepared to respond to a System Status service request from the switching function in such cases (because it has no way of specifying that it should not receive such requests).
    8. Note that if a computing function registers for system services it will support the ability to respond to any switching function System Status service requests it may receive. In particular, for implicit registrations, a CSTA-conformant computing function will always be able to support such requests from the switching function.
